,Recommended,324310,21618819,"Posted: 4 March, 2016",all,Jonathan,"It's not every time I review a game, but I thought the need to review this game was high! Bus Simulator 16 is set in the town of Sunny Springs. Not only are you a bus driver, but you have to deal with a variety of events that happen around you!Driving the BusThe driving and stability of the bus is relatively easy. I'm currently using a Logitech G27 and I'm able to turn the steering wheel with no problem. However, I feel it can be quite stiff sometimes, but I'm sure this will be improved.The PassengersThe passengers are amazing. You get a variety of different talks whilst driving your bus, from calling in sick to work, talking to fellow passengers etc. Other than when I give passengers their ticket, they say 'Thank you dear'. There are also other events including asking a passenger to move so you can close the doors, helping a wheelchair user onto the bus where you may need to get out of your seat and operate it manually or press a button at the cab, turning the air con/heating up or down to the passengers' wish or even dealing with drunk passengers. Pedestrians also relatively behave probably, I do get the occasional event where a passenger walks out in front of me at a crossing and your current drive would end immediately.There are also other events including fixing a jammed door, where you need to get out of your seat and manually close the door.Graphics and TexturesThe graphics overall are pretty good. I've been hearing reports about the textures glitching out and turning to grey, however I have not been getting this problem. A feature I do like is when it's raining and the trees blow around. Unfortunately, when it is raining, you don't get any rain effects on the windscreen which was quite a disappointment. There are wipers, but there is no point in really using these.The AI VehiclesThe AI's behaviour in-game is very good, they will react to your indicators very well, like when you are pulling out of a bus stop, the car behind you will stop and let you out. There does seem to be a glitch where if you are sat in the cockpit, you won't be able to see the AI's lights (indicators, brake lights) but you will be able to see them from outside of the bus. This might explain to some people why they have been crashing into the back of AI cars, which I have done a couple of times.  AI will also behave probably when at traffic lights or junctions, so the developers have done a good job on coding the AI vehicles!The FPS I get in-gameThe FPS I get in-game is relatively good to keep it stable. I get around 40-50FPS overall when driving around or walking about in my office/garage. I have been looking at the reviews where some people have put a thumbs down because of the poor FPS they get in-game. I seem to be one of the lucky ones where I don't get any FPS problems and can play the game with no problem. However, I'm sure for those who are getting problems that there will be a patch relatively soon.Overall ConclusionOverall, I believe Bus Simulator 16 is a great simulator and is much better than the previous bus simulator I had, which was OMSI 2, which had no end of glitches, crashes and bad in-game optimization etc. It's not every day you get a good Bus Simulator like this, probably one of the best to date. There may be a few glitches and bugs there and there, but let's be grateful that we have a good Bus Simulator!"
,Recommended,324310,29726393,Posted: 5 February,all,Bad Whippet,"What's to like about it?Bus Simulator 16 does exactly what it says in the title (that's always a good start)!  You start out with a simple route and basic vehicle, and you drive the route to collect fares, keep to a timetable, avoid accidents and (hopefully) make a profit.  When you have enough money, you can hire new drivers, buy new vehicles and drive new routes too.  This is a true simulator (not necessarily a 'fun' game) so will likely feel a bit dry for anyone looking for heaps of excitement!Whether you enjoy this simulator or not will come down to how well you treat the simulation.  If you ignore kerbs, corners and road positioning, you can hare from stop to stop and then it's done - boring.  However, if you play it as a trainee driver and use your mirrors to make perfect corners without clipping kerbs or hitting anything, (ie a bit of real-life stuff), then you will get much more challenge and simulation experience out of the game.  A wheel is recommended for the driving, and there is a full set of cockpit controls that you can click on in 3D view (a little like Train Simulator) or you can use button shortcuts instead.I've driven several buses and coaches and I have to say the handling of the buses in-game isn't bad at all.  Some things are simulated perfectly, like mirrors and cornering (and reversing into your garage if you're feeling particularly cocky)!  This is as real as it gets and Bus Simulator 16 nails it perfectly.  Wheels on a bus or coach are a few feet behind the driver, so you must drive out into the junction straight before you can begin the steer.  Unlike a car, steering is not a single arm-wrench of the wheel and skid around that corner (pity)!  It's a nouanced set of movements (steer the front, straighten, steer again for rear wheels) that is difficult at first, but it's very true to life.  This is what the game does exceptionally well.  In reality, overall steering tends to be a little lighter and easier than is represented by the game, with only slight steer giving quite a turn, but the game wanted more steering than I would usually expect.  That could be that I don't have my in-game wheel settings balanced correctly though.Talking of wheels, many are supported but do check the forums as some people are having a few problems.  The newer Logitech 920 isn't currently working properly (the devs are looking at it).  As for older wheels like the Logitech G25 and 27, they do work after some fiddling.  It entails downloading Logitech's newest driver which no longer supports the G25/27 (nice one Logitech in forcing obsolescence in £200+ game controllers) and taking from the new drivers a DLL file and adding it to the game (all explained in the game forums), then reinstalling an older G25/27 supporting driver.  A nuisance, but doable.Anything not so good?The graphics are a bit basic for today's PCs, though they're not necessarily so important as the game mechanics are in a simulation title.  There is ONLY right-hand driving, which sucks for anyone in a left-hand drive country because this game actually makes quite a neat training aid.  The overall vehicle handling and steering response (particularly on straight roads) tends to be a little too heavy (steering of these vehicles is typically very light).  Oh, and there is no driver customisation which is a minor point, but being able to customise features, skin-tone and gender could have been a neat addition.  That's nit-picking though.Will you like it?If you're looking for a pure simulator title, then this is a good place to start.  It offers everything you need in setting up and driving basic bus routes and is actually good enough as a training aid for driving any long, non-articulated vehicle in managing corners well (all mirrors are recreated perfectly).  However, if you're looking for more of a 'game' experience, it might be a title you won't enjoy so much."
76561198159426714,Recommended,324310,21601476,"Posted: 3 March, 2016",all,nzyowie,"This is a very engaging and interesting game. You do more than just drive a bus - you also have to manage your own bus company, organise routes, deal with a variety of interesting situations (bus malfunctions, demanding passengers etc.), buy new buses, hire new drivers and so on. You get missions that help you unlock new features. You're never short of something to do.Bus Simulator 16 is made by the same people who developed Bus Simulator 2012, albeit with a different partner this time. I gave Bus Simulator 2012 a negative review, but I am happy to say that Bus Simulator 16 is a vast improvement - with one exception. Bus Simulator 2012 had awful frame rates, and unfortunately, so does Bus Simulator 2016 at present. I played on medium graphic settings with a pretty powerful computer, but found the gameplay very laggy and choppy, although just bearable. But I can play games like Euro Truck Simulator 2 or Train Simulator 2016 on high settings and have no FPS issues. So this is an area that needs work. And apparently, the developers are working on it, so hopefully performance will be much better soon.Some areas where Bus Simulator 2016 has improved on BS 2012 include keyboard steering (much, MUCH better, more like Euro Truck or American Truck Simulator steering now), AI traffic (much more sensible, accidents are usually due to your bad driving rather than their stupidity) and user-friendliness of the bus interior (no more password to enter, selling tickets is now much more efficiently handled). And of course, it introduces new things that were never seen in BS 2012, like the whole company management deal, missions and so on.Other than the need for performance optimisation, I have few complaints about this game. It is definitely the best bus simulator since OMSI 2, and has real potential to give the latter a serious run for its money. I am more than happy to recommend it."
