76561198030720390,Recommended,324310,22202095,"Posted: 2 April, 2016",all,Deltavee,"This game sits between games like ETS 2 and Omsi 2. Like ETS 2 the world is open and explorable, and there is a managment part where you run your company. Unlike Omsi 2 the game actually looks good and runs well, though the details of each bus are nowhere near as involved.It /is/ a simulator, you have to start the bus, use indicators, open doors, all by either clicking on items on the screen, using the keyboard or mapping them to controller buttons. While its somewhat arcadey there is a learning curve but its enjoyable discovering how the bus works and how you need to use it in the world. The developers seem to be listening and working hard to update most of the complaints they've recieved. For example the orientation of the gps map or auto turn off of indicators when you straighten out the steering wheel. The game play is smooth, I haven't quantified the framerates but it doesn't stutter or go slowly unlike Omsi 2 which is notorious for doing that even on massive high end systems.The sound quality is high, though somewhat generic. The only complaint I have is how harsh some of the penalties are. Hit a pedestrian? Game stops and you have to start the scenario over, even if it happens as your pulling into your garage. Accidents are very costly, as are speeding fines. All well and good for sim realism I guess but annoying. Finally, the game is fairly easy to use with my G27 steering set up, though I did have to futz a little with the settings to get things nice. Again, more like ETS 2 in that and a hell of a lot better than Omsi 2.Overall I give it four and a half out of five stars.A pleasant and thoughtful game that keeps your attention and is challanging enough not to bore you easily but not so hard your wondering why the hell you wasted money on it (yes I'm looking at you Omsi).System specs: 4790K i7, Gigabyte 980ti G1, 16 gigs Crucial memory."
