,Recommended,324310,28823365,"Posted: 30 December, 2016",all,Senneca Syprian™,"I seriously can not understand where the hate this game is getting comes from. It does exactly what it says on the ""box"", and does it very well. While not a perfect game by any means, this is a great effort from a smaller company, that fills a niche I've personally desired for over 10 years.When I was a young lass, back in my high school days, I used to take the public bus to commute to school and back, and also to travel from place to place on my weekends. I spent hundreds of IRL hours on various models of IRL busses, and I always wanted to try driving one. This game finally allowed me to live my fantasy. I honestly never thought a company would ever bother to make a bus driving game, but Bus Simulator 16 actually goes above and beyond that, and includes management and a bit of strategy as well.In Bus Simulator 16, you'll assume the role of a man who has just started a bus company, and won a minor contract with the local city of Sunny Springs, and a few cheap models of busses to chose from. You'll start alone, with a limited amount of startup cash, with a small area available to you. Over time you'll prove to the city you can handle bigger contracts, which will give you access to more districts of the city, and more modern/expensive models of busses.Gameplay consists of 2 parts: driving your routes, and managing your company. Your company can be single player (offline) or co-op multiplayer (online), but if you choose to bring your company online it can not be undone.Managing your company consists of buying/maintaining busses, hiring/firing NPC (or other online players if you go multiplayer) drivers, and planning routes. You can paint your fleet various colors, and add advertisements to generate extra income.Driving is the heart of the game and you will need to drive each new route yourself first before you can assign that route to an NPC driver. You will be able to choose various models of busses to drive, including bendy (two car) busses. The in game tutorial is quick, easy to understand, and teaches you everything you need to know about driving. You will need to make all the stops on the route, while obaying traffic laws, keeping your schedule on time, charging passengers the correct fare, and making change, and accomidating any unexpected situation that may pop up.Driving the bus feels natural, and the controls are easy to pick up. The AI is dumb, and pedestrians will occasionaly step out in front of your rig, or change lanes into your path, but for the most part you can predict their behavior.  Weather, traffic jams, and various events (bouncing drunk passengers, unjamming stuck doors, extending the ramp for wheelchair bound passengers, etc.) will add variety to your routes.The dev is German, so the city/roads/laws are very european; As an American, this took some getting used to. In America, bus drivers expect you to have exact change for your fare, and carry no change. I don't know how they do things in Germany, but in this game you are expected to do math and count out correct change for everyone. This is the one part of the game that really sucks, but you'll soon memorize the appropriate amounts for each bill/fare and life will go on.The graphics are pretty bare bones, and honestly, what can you expect from a small dev making a game that will appeal to a niche group of players? I'm just happy this game got made at all. You will encounter some bugs here and there, but nothing that breaks the game or prevents you from running it smoothly (at least in my experience).Overall I would say if you're one of the people who is intrigued by the prospect of managing/driving for your own bus company, you should buy this game. It does what it sets out to do, and it works without crashing. What more can you ask for?"
76561198043142058,Recommended,324310,21636589,"Posted: 5 March, 2016",all,kahnguest,"I have changed my review of this game thanks to MrTP for helping me out ( see comments below on graphic cards to make sure Steam is using your computers highend  graphic card)Make sure you have the correct specs otherwise you wont enjoy this gameFor $25 this sim is worth it -- its a great bus sim and very easy to play , a lot of detail has gone into the design of the management system of the game alone ..We dont have much choice when it comes to Bus sims , but by far for me -- this is the best I have played and will contine to play ( thanks again MrTP ).....................................................................................I recommend this game and I also dont recommend this game -- ..  I say yes get it---  ONLY if you have a very high end computer - I have a $3000 Alienware system it it stuggled it keep up with the framerate -- i had to turn down the settings to lowest to get  somewhat ok gametime but I feel its overpriced for me personally considering the really bad graphics I have to put up with to play it at a basic level ..  dont waste your time if you have a limited hardware systemI can run GTA V on Ultra but cant run a square bus around a ten block city -- mmmmm go figureIf you have the specs required -- Play it -- its one of the better featured bus sims out on the market for the priceFROM MrTP  :From my experience you can increase your performance very much by:1. Making sure that steam uses the correct graphic card to run BS16 (please see here:http://gaming.stackexchange.com/questions/72567/can-i-force-steam-to-use-my-nvidia-gpu-instead-of-the-integrated-intel-card/72576#72576)2. Adjusting your graphic setting within BS16.To increase your fps rate please try to:- simply reduce the viewing distance- make sure that the option ""Always Update Bus Mirrors"" is deactivated"
